/*
 * Smart_Probe_H2_v5_band.c
 * ============================================================
 * All changes from v5_band(CHANGE 6) retained. New change in this revision:
 *
 *  CHANGE 7 ? Reduced sf EEPROM round-trip rounding error (0.05 -> 0.02 step):
 *    - calib_ee_write_entry()/calib_ee_read_entry() previously stored sf as
 *      a SIGNED offset-from-1.00, round((sf-1.0)/0.05), range ~ -5.4..7.35,
 *      worst-case round-trip error +-0.025. In practice this meant *1CAL
 *      results like sf=0.93 could come back as 0.95 (or worse) after a
 *      power cycle, purely from EEPROM quantization -- not a logic bug,
 *      just a coarse grid.
 *    - Fixed: sf is now stored DIRECTLY (no "-1.0" offset) as an UNSIGNED
 *      uint8, round(sf/0.02), range 0.00..5.10, worst-case round-trip
 *      error +-0.01 -- less than half the old error, using the SAME
 *      single EEPROM byte (no layout change, CALIB_ENTRY_EE_BYTES stays
 *      10). Safe because sf only ever comes from *1CAL's divisor math
 *      (starting at 1.00, repeatedly multiplied/divided by
 *      1 + steps*P.sf_step), which can never legitimately produce sf <= 0
 *      -- so no sign bit is needed, freeing up range for finer resolution.
 *    - CALIB_EE_MAGIC_VAL bumped (0xA9 -> 0xAA) so any EEPROM written by
 *      older firmware (signed/0.05 encoding) is treated as invalid and
 *      reloaded from defaults on first boot, rather than being misread
 *      under the new unsigned/0.02 interpretation.
 *
 * ============================================================
 * All changes from v5_band(dynSF) retained. New change in that revision:
 *
 *  CHANGE 6 ? Fixed sf EEPROM encoding losing sub-1.0 scaling factors:
 *    - calib_ee_write_entry() previously stored sf as round((sf-1.0)/0.05)
 *      in an UNSIGNED byte and clamped negative results to 0. Any *1CAL
 *      result with sf < 1.0 (routine, since cross-concentration division
 *      can easily push sf under 1.0) therefore got silently rewritten as
 *      sf = 1.00 the moment it hit EEPROM -- it read back correctly from
 *      RAM immediately after calibration, but reverted to 1.00 on the
 *      very next power cycle.
 *    - Fixed: the byte is now interpreted as a SIGNED int8 (-128..127),
 *      so sf can legitimately be stored and reloaded anywhere from about
 *      -5.4 to 7.35 in the same 0.05 steps as before. No layout/size
 *      change (still 1 byte per row) -- just correct rounding + no more
 *      negative clamp.
 *    - CALIB_EE_MAGIC_VAL bumped (0xA8 -> 0xA9) so any EEPROM written by
 *      older firmware is treated as invalid and reloaded from defaults
 *      on first boot, rather than being misread under the new signed
 *      interpretation.
 *
 * ============================================================
 * All changes from v4_crc retained. New change in that revision:
 *
 *  CHANGE 5 ? Dynamic scaling factor (SF) instead of baked-in p_mv:
 *      stays the ORIGINAL, un-scaled calibration point (in RAM and in
 *      EEPROM). Only the .sf field is updated for rows with
 *      ppm >= CALIB_HIGH_PPM (5000) -- exactly as before, sub-5000
 *      rows are never touched and their sf stays pinned at 1.00.
 *    - calib_interp() now computes an "effective" centre EMF for every
 *      row on the fly via calib_eff_mv() = p_mv * sf, and uses that
 *      value everywhere p_mv used to be used directly (clamping,
 *      band-snap, interpolation). band_mv itself is never scaled,
 *      matching the old behaviour exactly. Net predicted ppm for any
 *      given measured EMF is numerically identical to the old
 *      "multiply-and-store" approach.
 *    - New command *RESETCAL# resets sf back to 1.00 on every row of
 *      both CALIB_FAST and CALIB_AN (p_mv/ppm/band_mv untouched) and
 *      saves both tables to EEPROM -- one command undoes any number of
 *      prior *1CAL calls instantly.
 *    - GET PARAMS calib dump now also prints "eff=" (p_mv * sf) next to
 *      the raw p_mv and sf for each row, so the currently-active
 *      calibration point is visible alongside the stored raw one.
 *
 * ============================================================
 * All changes from v4_crc retained. New change in that revision:
 *
 *  CHANGE 4 ? Band-based calibration interpolation (mirrors Python v2.9.9):
 *    - CalibEntry now stores a third field: band_mv (float, ?tolerance).
 *    - calib_interp() updated to band-aware logic:
 *        1. If p_val <= first_emf - band0  ? clamp to first ppm
 *        2. If p_val >= last_emf  + bandN  ? clamp to last ppm
 *        3. Walk rows: if p_val in [emf-band, emf+band] ? snap to ppm
 *        4. Otherwise interpolate linearly between upper edge of lower
 *           band and lower edge of upper band (not centre points).
 *    - band_mv = 0.0 rows behave identically to the old point interpolation.
 *    - EEPROM layout updated: each CalibEntry now 9 bytes (was 12).
 *      New EEPROM address constants defined; old magic values are
 *      invalidated on first boot ? defaults load cleanly, no corruption.
 *    - Default tables include band values matching Python DEFAULT_PARAMS.
 *    - SET CAL / SET ANCAL commands extended to accept optional band_mv.
 *    - GET PARAMS output includes band column for each calib row.
 *    - All other engine logic, EEPROM params, MB save/load: UNCHANGED.
 *
 * ============================================================
 * All changes from v3 retained. New change in this revision:
 *
 *  CHANGE 3 ? Real CRC-16/IBM in frame output (replaces static 0xAB/0xCD):
 *    - Added frame_crc16() using the same CRC-16/IBM (Modbus) algorithm
 *      from the reference Modbus implementation.
 *    - CRC is computed over the payload bytes only (B02..B08 for data frame,
 *      B02..B20 for diagnostic frame) ? excludes 0x0A start and 0x0D end.
 *    - CRC bytes sent lo byte first, then hi byte (same swap as Modbus).
 *    - tx_send_int32_be() kept for internal use; payload now assembled
 *      into a buffer first, CRC computed, then transmitted.
 *
 * ============================================================
 * All fixes from v2_fixed retained. New changes from v3:
 *
 *  CHANGE 1 ? Warmup state machine rework:
 *    - Collection window is now hard-fixed at 400 samples
 *      (independent of P.warmup which is kept for other uses).
 *    - During the 400-sample collection window: Col 8 = 0.
 *    - After 400 samples, a separate 50-sample rolling SD window
 *      (wu_chk_buf) starts. Samples accumulate silently for exactly 50,
 *      then both conditions are evaluated ONCE:
 *        condition A: wu_chk_sd() < WARMUP_SD_THRESH   (SD of those 50)
 *        condition B: no stored MB  OR
 *                     fabsf(wu_mean() - stored_mother_baseline) <= WARMUP_PROX_MV
 *      Both must pass to transition directly to WARMUP_RUNNING (Col 8 = 4).
 *      Either failing keeps Col 8 = 1. The 50-sample window slides so
 *      a settling signal will eventually pass.
 *    - wu_mean() (400-sample mean) is used for prox check and baseline seed.
 *    - *TARE# exits warmup at any point (forces WARMUP_RUNNING).
 *    - *IGNORE_PROX# still works as before.
 *
 *  CHANGE 2 ? *stop# command (one-shot check):
 *    - On receipt, checks: II == -1.0f AND rec_pct == 100.0f
 *                          AND or_state == OR_NORMAL
 *      * Conditions NOT met ? print "BRING PROBE TO AIR / WAIT"
 *        once, resume normal operation. User must re-issue *stop#.
 *      * Conditions met     ? save mother_baseline to EEPROM,
 *        print "OK_STOPPED", set is_running = false,
 *        loop waiting for *start# (same as initial boot gate).
 *
 * 11-Column UART output:
 *  [1] RefR  [2] EMF_mV  [3] DispPPM  [4] Type  [5] H2_Flag
 *  [6] Rec_Status  [7] OR_Status  [8] Warmup  [9] PostCnt
 *  [10] ProbeState  [11] NthMode (F=low-ppm-thresh active, T=normal-thresh active)
 *
 * Col 8 Warmup values:
 *   0 = collecting (first 400 samples)
 *   1 = SD or prox check failing (was 1+2 previously)
 *   3 = ready for tare (both checks passed)
 *   4 = running normally
 */

